considering using KryoException serialization, which inherits from RuntimeException and includes stack trace elements and module names. I need to think about whether stack trace elements are serializable in a native image; maybe they are. Using String might be safer, but it doesn't include metadata. However, Java serialization for Strings tends to work well. I’m wondering which option is more reliable overall. It feels a bit tricky to decide here!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_2sARJ9CWudXTq91DJAwGmoGt|fc_032077860276de100169f29c385d4c8191a5697b54091b188f", "name": "write", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/com.esotericsoftware/kryo-shaded/3.0.3/src/test/java/com_esotericsoftware/kryo_shaded/JavaSerializerTest.java", "content": "/*\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\n *\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\n */\npackage com_esotericsoftware.kryo_shaded;\n\nimport com.esotericsoftware.kryo.Kryo;\nimport com.esotericsoftware.kryo.io.Input;\nimport com.esotericsoftware.kryo.io.Output;\nimport com.esotericsoftware.kryo.serializers.JavaSerializer;\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\n\nimport static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;\n\npublic class JavaSerializerTest {\n    @Test\n    void writesAndReadsObjectsUsingJavaSerializationStreams() {\n        JavaSerializer serializer = new JavaSerializer();\n        Output output = new Output(128, -1);\n\n        serializer.write(new Kryo(), output, \"kryo-java-serialization\");\n\n        Object restored = serializer.read(new Kryo(), new Input(output.toBytes()), String.class);\n\n        assertThat(restored).isEqualTo(\"kryo-java-serialization\");\n    }\n}\n"}, "partialJson": "{\"path\":\"tests/src/com.esotericsoftware/kryo-shaded/3.0.3/src/test/java/com_esotericsoftware/kryo_shaded/JavaSerializerTest.java\",\"content\":\"/*\\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\\n *\\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\\n */\\npackage com_esotericsoftware.kryo_shaded;\\n\\nimport com.esotericsoftware.kryo.Kryo;\\nimport com.esotericsoftware.kryo.io.Input;\\nimport com.esotericsoftware.kryo.io.Output;\\nimport com.esotericsoftware.kryo.serializers.JavaSerializer;\\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\\n\\nimport static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;\\n\\npublic class JavaSerializerTest {\\n    @Test\\n    void writesAndReadsObjectsUsingJavaSerializationStreams() {\\n        JavaSerializer serializer = new JavaSerializer();\\n        Output output = new Output(128, -1);\\n\\n        serializer.write(new Kryo(), output, \\\"kryo-java-serialization\\\");\\n\\n        Object restored = serializer.read(new Kryo(), new Input(output.toBytes()), String.class);\\n\\n        assertThat(restored).isEqualTo(\\\"kryo-java-serialization\\\");\\n    }\\n}\\n\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1232, "output": 1172, "cacheRead": 12288, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 14692, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777507370822, "responseId": "resp_032077860276de100169f29c2b734081919686ab21427753fd"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_2sARJ9CWudXTq91DJAwGmoGt|fc_032077860276de100169f29c385d4c8191a5697b54091b188f", "toolName": "write", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Successfully wrote 988 bytes to tests/src/com.esotericsoftware/kryo-shaded/3.0.3/src/test/java/com_esotericsoftware/kryo_shaded/JavaSerializerTest.java"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1777507386348}]}
